---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Sartre: Existence Precedes Essence – Radical Freedom and the Creation of the Self | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Sartre</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Existence Precedes Essence – Radical Freedom and the Creation of the Self
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					The existentialist insight that there is no pre-given human nature or fixed self. You create your essence through your choices and actions and bear full responsibility for who you become.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong>
					First Sartre in his own terms. Then inspirations for Identity Engineering.
					Then additions from Identity Engineering perspective.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Existence Precedes Essence</div>
					<p>
						Jean-Paul Sartre’s central claim in existentialism is that **existence precedes essence**. There is no pre-given human nature, no fixed self or soul that defines you in advance. You exist first, and through your choices, actions, and projects you create what you are — your essence.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						In *Existentialism is a Humanism* (1946) Sartre writes: “Man is nothing else but what he makes of himself.” This is both a liberation and a burden: you are “condemned to be free.”
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Bad Faith and Authentic Existence</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core concepts (Sartre):</strong> Bad faith (mauvaise foi) is the self-deception in which one denies one’s radical freedom and pretends to be a fixed thing (e.g., identifying completely with a social role or character). Authentic existence means fully owning one’s freedom and responsibility.
					</div>
					<p>
						The famous example of the waiter who plays at being a waiter — over-identifying with the role to escape the anxiety of freedom. In bad faith, one treats oneself as an object (en-soi) rather than as a conscious, choosing subject (pour-soi).
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Authenticity requires facing the anguish of absolute freedom and choosing one’s projects without excuses or external determination.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Sartre:</strong> identity is not discovered or given; it is created through choices and actions. There is no fixed essence — only the ongoing project of becoming.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> radical freedom as the ground for deliberate geometric design; bad faith as the opposite of conscious curvature and high-Mass commitment; and full responsibility as the ethical core of the Architect level.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Existence precedes essence = radical designability:</strong> Sartre provides the strongest philosophical foundation for the claim that identity is fundamentally designable. There is no pre-given Stem or substance; the Stem itself is something we constitute through choices and projects.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Bad faith as anti-geometry:</strong> Bad faith is the refusal to consciously curve one’s identity geometry. It is low-Mass role-playing and denial of freedom — the opposite of the Executor → Author → Architect arc.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Radical responsibility as Architect ethics:</strong> Because you create your essence, you are fully responsible for the identity geometry you produce. This aligns perfectly with the forensic and Architect dimensions of the framework.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Freedom as causal entropy maximizer:</strong> Sartre’s absolute freedom is the condition for maximizing open futures. Every choice is a curvature of the possibility space. Identity Engineering supplies the geometric tools to make this freedom conscious and effective.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> Sartre emphasizes radical freedom and the creation of essence through action in a phenomenological-existential register. He complements Hume’s bundle view (no fixed self) by stressing that the bundle is actively constituted through projects. Compared to Jung, Sartre is less focused on unconscious integration and more on conscious choice and responsibility. He pushes the design-oriented nature of Identity Engineering to its most radical conclusion: you are nothing but what you make of yourself through deliberate curvature of your identity geometry.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary: Jean-Paul Sartre, <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Being and Nothingness</em> (1943), <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Existentialism is a Humanism</em> (1946).
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/sartre/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Sartre</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Sartre is the major existentialist voice that radicalizes freedom and responsibility. He completes the modern sequence by showing that identity is not only constructed (Hume) or integrated (Jung) but radically chosen in every moment. This anchor makes the Executor → Author → Architect arc philosophically inescapable.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
